    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-100 mb-4">Detailed Comparison</h2>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-200 mb-3">Pricing and Value for Money</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-400 mb-6">Cambly uses a subscription model that gives you unlimited access to native English speakers for a flat weekly or monthly fee. Plans start around $15.99 per week for the basic 30-minute option three times per week, with higher tiers offering unlimited minutes. This flat-rate approach is exceptional value if you plan to practice several times per week, as there is no per-minute or per-session cost to worry about. Verbling charges on a per-lesson basis, with tutors typically starting from $12 per hour. The absence of a subscription means you pay only when you book a session, but frequent learners will spend significantly more on Verbling than they would on Cambly's unlimited model. For pure volume of speaking practice, Cambly wins on price. Verbling's pay-per-lesson model is more transparent but less economical for daily practice.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-200 mb-3">Tutor Quality and Credentials</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-400 mb-6">Cambly connects you exclusively with native English speakers from countries like the United States, the United Kingdom, and Australia. These tutors are not necessarily professional teachers, but they provide authentic conversational practice with people who speak English as their first language. The quality varies by individual tutor, but the platform is straightforward and the tutors are generally warm and encouraging. Verbling takes a different approach by focusing on professionally trained educators. Every tutor on Verbling has been vetted for teaching credentials, and many hold formal qualifications in language instruction. This makes Verbling particularly strong for learners who need structured curriculum, business English, or exam preparation with a qualified instructor. If you want authentic conversation with native speakers, Cambly is the better choice. If you need a professional teacher with a structured lesson plan, Verbling is the stronger option.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-200 mb-3">Access and Scheduling Flexibility</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-400 mb-6">This is one of the clearest differences between the two platforms. Cambly's subscription model lets you log in at any time and connect with an available native speaker for an impromptu conversation session. There is no need to schedule ahead or book in advance. The experience is closer to walking into a coffee shop where a native speaker happens to be available. Verbling requires you to choose a specific tutor, browse their available time slots, and book a session in advance. This is more like traditional tutoring where you plan your lesson in advance and work through a prepared agenda. The scheduling approach suits learners who prefer structure, but Cambly is far more flexible for anyone who wants to practice on the fly or build a daily speaking habit without friction.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-200 mb-3">Speaking Confidence and Conversational Practice</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-400 mb-6">Cambly is purpose-built for conversational fluency. The informal, open-ended nature of Cambly sessions removes the pressure of a structured lesson and lets you simply talk. You can discuss anything from your day to your goals, and the tutors are trained to keep conversations flowing naturally. This format is especially valuable for beginners who feel anxious about speaking English, as the low-pressure environment builds confidence faster than a formal classroom setting. Verbling sessions tend to be more curriculum-driven. Tutors typically follow a lesson plan, introduce grammar points, correct mistakes more explicitly, and assign homework or follow-up tasks. This is excellent for targeted skill development but can feel intimidating for learners who simply need to practice the act of speaking without evaluation. If your main goal is to become a more confident English speaker, Cambly's unlimited, pressure-free model is the more effective choice.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-200 mb-3">Platform and Technology</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-400 mb-6">Both platforms offer their own built-in video conferencing tools that work directly in your browser without needing additional software. Cambly has developed a dedicated app for iOS and Android, making it easy to practice on mobile devices throughout the day. Verbling also has mobile apps available for both platforms and includes features such as lesson notes that your tutor can share after each session. Both platforms use reliable video technology, but Cambly's always-on availability means the technology serves a spontaneous, on-demand purpose. Verbling's system is designed around the booked lesson workflow. Neither platform is clearly superior in terms of technology, but the difference in access models shapes how you will use each tool in practice.</p>
  </section>

